 book reveals how the pandemic has intensified socio-economic problems and inequalities across the world whilst offering visions for a better future informed by social movements and public sociology. Bringing together experts from 27 countries, the authors explore the global echoes of the pandemic and the different responses adopted by governments, policy makers and activists. The new expressions of social action, and forms of solidarity and protest, are discussed in detail, from the Black Lives Matter protests to the French Strike Movement and the Lebanese Uprising. This is a unique global analysis on the current crisis and the contemporary world and its outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xEconomic aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xPolitical aspects. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xSocial aspects. 0aSocial movements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnastasoupoulos, Emanuelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArata, Nicolás, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAraujo, Kathya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBachelet, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanerjee, Supurna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarros, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatthyány, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBizberg, Ilán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo